Symptoms, protection measures and transmission theories: all that is known about the deadly virus. Coronaviruses are a family of viruses that can give rise to diseases in humans. The deadly virus was identified on January 7, 2020 in China, after, on 31 December 2019, several cases of pneumonia of unknown cause in workers and people who attended the fish market, Live seafood and birds in the city of Wuhan, Hubei province.
So far 304 people have died which made the WHO (World Health Organization) to declare international public health emergency. This Friday were reported more than a thousand new cases and, at international level, more than 14380 infected were already confirmed.

Symptoms regarding signs and symptoms, the National Health Service (SNS) warns that patients may present symptoms of acute respiratory infection as cough, fever and respiratory difficulties.
In the most serious cases "can lead to severe pneumonia with acute respiratory failure, renal bankruptcy and other organs and eventual death," writes the SNS on the site.
Transmission risk Agreement with the European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC), there is a moderate probability of importation of cases in the European Union countries.
ECDC has assured that, provided that the practices of prevention and control of infection are met, the probability of secondary transmission is low.
Treatment Treatment for people infected with deadly virus is done taking into account the signs and symptoms that are presented. To date there is no vaccine that heals the virus but investigations are already being made in that direction.
Protecting measures World Health Organization (WHO) recommended some hygiene measures and food security practices to reduce the transmission of the disease, such as:

Wash your hands frequently, especially after being in direct contact with people who are sick;
Avoid unprotected contact with wild animals or fifth;
Avoid contact close with patients with respiratory infections;
Adopt respiratory label measures: cover mouth and nose when sneezing or coughing;
Wash your hands whenever sneezing, coughing or whistling;

What to do if it is traveling the World Health Organization does not recommend commercial exchanges for China. If the destination of the trip is the Chinese country, you must follow the recommendations of China's health authorities and the recommendations described by WHO. If, on the other hand, you are returning from affected areas that have symptoms of the disease, should, before you go to a hospital, call SNS24 to report on your health condition and follow the guidelines that are indicated.
What are the world zones affected by the deadly virus? So far cases were recorded in 25 zones of the world. In addition to China's continental territory (the most affected area), cases of infection in Sweden have been reported Warning: Can only detect less than 5000 characters

First case of coronavirus confirmed in Belgium. The authorities of Belgium today confirmed the first case in the country of the new Coronavirus (2019-NCOV) in a person who was repatriated from the Chinese city of Wuhan, a focus of an outbreak of the disease, which already killed 426 people. The Belgian Ministry of Health has released today that the person has good health and does not show any symptoms of the disease.

This person was among nine Belgians repatriated from Wuhan, China, which occurred this weekend. The infected patient was taken to a special hospital for more care, while the other repatriates remain under observation.




